    <!-- bio Section -->
    <section id="bio" class="about-section text-center">
        <div class="container">
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-lg-8 mx-auto">
                    <h2 class="text-white mb-4">Autobiography</h2>
                    <p class="text-white-50">
                        At a young age, I didn’t know music would later become my passion. My parents bought me an acoustic guitar and signed me up for guitar lessons, but beyond having an affinity with the instrument, I wasn’t motivated to learn how to sight read and practice at home. Little did I know that 8 years later, in high school, the sound of an electric guitar would hit me right to my soul: Master of Puppets by Metallica. I was hooked. Call it teenage angst or just a sound to express how I felt inside, something inside me woke up that day. The first time around, I was given a guitar. Now, I was being called to it! <br><br>

                        I had to do a lot of chores that summer to earn my electric guitar starter pack set. In my last year of high school, I formed my first band called “Highjack’d”. This is when I discovered my passion for classic rock and the blues. It felt natural to express myself with a guitar in hand. From angry to happy, I could let it all out on chord at a time.<br> <br>
                        Artists such as<strong> Aerosmith, GNR, Thin Lizzy, SRV, Boston, Lynyrd Skynyrd, ACDC, The Rolling Stones, The Beatles, The Black Crowes, Motley Crüe, Alice Cooper, Buddy Guy, Cream, KISS, Led Zeppelin, Skid Row, Supertramp, System of a down, The Doors and Jimi Hendrix,</strong> just to name a few, were my greatest influences. <br><br>

                        After my first band began drifting apart, the singer and I eventually met a drummer, a bass player and a guitar player with whom we had great musical chemistry. We became the band “Monroe.” I played with these boys for 4 years and my skills really took a leap during this period. We learned covers, wrote original songs and played several shows around Montreal. Unfortunately, the band had a fallout. Many bruised egos & broken instruments later, we parted ways. <br><br>

                        For almost a year and half after, I had lost my musical spark and felt directionless. On a whim, I booked a flight to LA — something I’d always wanted to do—hoping to shake things up and find my way again. All I knew is that I wanted to be on a stage or around a stage. Musician’s Institute seemed to me like the most promising option. I got a loan from the bank, saved up a lot of money and with my parent’s help, moved to Los Angeles, California. I learned from the likes of <strong>David Isaac, Barry Rudolph, Jim Morgan, Jerry Christie, Mehdi Hassine, Billy Thornton, Ted Blaisdell </strong> to name a few. Around this time, I formed a band with some friends from school who came to LA from all over the world. We recorded songs and played a few gigs in town. I had the time of my life.<br><br>


                        After a year in LA, I came back to Montreal and worked as a sound engineer in festivals, events and for bands. For a little over a year now, I have been playing and keeping busy with the band “Crash of Rhinos.” I’m currently looking to play as many live gigs as I possibly can.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
